	<div class="intro-section">
		<p class="lead">Spring is the ideal time to inspect, clean, and maintain your fence before Stockton's intense summer heat arrives. Winter rain and cool temperatures can reveal problems, while mild spring weather provides perfect conditions for repairs and staining. This comprehensive checklist ensures your fence is ready to withstand another Central Valley summer.</p>
	</div>

	<h2>Why Spring Maintenance Matters</h2>
	<p>Spring maintenance isn't just about appearance—it extends fence life and prevents costly repairs:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Weather window:</strong> Ideal temperatures (50-80°F) for staining and sealing</li>
		<li><strong>Winter damage assessment:</strong> Rain and wind may have caused issues</li>
		<li><strong>Pre-summer preparation:</strong> Protect against UV damage and heat stress</li>
		<li><strong>Prevent escalation:</strong> Small problems become big (and expensive) if ignored</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Complete Spring Inspection Checklist</h2>

	<h3>Structural Inspection</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>☐ Walk entire fence line noting any issues</li>
		<li>☐ Check posts for leaning (use level if needed)</li>
		<li>☐ Inspect post bases for rot or damage</li>
		<li>☐ Look for loose, warped, or missing boards</li>
		<li>☐ Test fence stability by gently pushing sections</li>
		<li>☐ Examine rails for sagging or damage</li>
		<li>☐ Check for ground erosion around posts</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Hardware Inspection</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>☐ Tighten loose screws and nails</li>
		<li>☐ Replace rusty or corroded fasteners</li>
		<li>☐ Check gate hinges for proper function</li>
		<li>☐ Test gate latches and locks</li>
		<li>☐ Lubricate squeaky hinges</li>
		<li>☐ Inspect decorative hardware (post caps, etc.)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Surface Condition</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>☐ Look for peeling or flaking stain/paint</li>
		<li>☐ Check for mold, mildew, or algae growth</li>
		<li>☐ Identify areas of significant fading</li>
		<li>☐ Note any splinters or rough areas</li>
		<li>☐ Inspect for insect damage (termites, carpenter ants)</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Cleaning Your Fence</h2>

	<h3>Wood Fence Cleaning</h3>
	<p><strong>For light dirt and dust:</strong></p>
	<ol>
		<li>Use garden hose with moderate pressure</li>
		<li>Work from top to bottom</li>
		<li>Let dry completely</li>
	</ol>

	<p><strong>For mold, mildew, or heavy soiling:</strong></p>
	<ol>
		<li>Mix solution: 1 part oxygen bleach to 4 parts water</li>
		<li>Apply with pump sprayer or brush</li>
		<li>Let sit 15-20 minutes</li>
		<li>Scrub with stiff brush if needed</li>
		<li>Rinse thoroughly with hose</li>
		<li>Allow 24-48 hours to dry before staining</li>
	</ol>

	<p><strong>Pressure washing tips:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Use wide fan tip (25-40 degree)</li>
		<li>Keep pressure under 1500 PSI for wood</li>
		<li>Maintain consistent distance (12-18 inches)</li>
		<li>Work with the wood grain</li>
		<li>Avoid lingering in one spot (causes damage)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Vinyl Fence Cleaning</h3>
	<ol>
		<li>Rinse with hose to remove loose debris</li>
		<li>Mix mild dish soap with water</li>
		<li>Apply with soft brush or sponge</li>
		<li>Rinse thoroughly</li>
		<li>For stubborn stains, use vinyl fence cleaner or magic eraser</li>
	</ol>

	<h3>Metal Fence Cleaning</h3>
	<ol>
		<li>Rinse with hose</li>
		<li>Apply mild soap solution</li>
		<li>Scrub with soft brush</li>
		<li>Rinse and dry to prevent water spots</li>
		<li>Check for rust spots requiring treatment</li>
	</ol>

	<h2>Staining and Sealing (Wood Fences)</h2>

	<h3>When to Stain</h3>
	<p>Spring staining is ideal when:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Temperatures are 50-80°F (check product specifications)</li>
		<li>No rain expected for 24-48 hours</li>
		<li>Wood is clean and completely dry</li>
		<li>Previous stain is fading or 2-3 years old</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Staining Process</h3>
	<ol>
		<li><strong>Test first:</strong> Apply to inconspicuous area to check color</li>
		<li><strong>Protect surroundings:</strong> Cover plants, walkways, structures</li>
		<li><strong>Apply evenly:</strong> Use brush, roller, or sprayer</li>
		<li><strong>Work with the grain:</strong> Maintain consistent direction</li>
		<li><strong>Avoid puddles:</strong> Apply thin, even coats</li>
		<li><strong>Back-brush:</strong> If spraying, follow with brush for penetration</li>
		<li><strong>Allow drying:</strong> Follow product recommendations before second coat</li>
	</ol>

	<h3>Stockton-Specific Staining Tips</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Choose UV-resistant stains for our intense sun</li>
		<li>Apply in morning or evening, not midday heat</li>
		<li>Semi-transparent stains show wood grain but need more frequent reapplication</li>
		<li>Solid stains last longer but hide wood character</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Common Repairs</h2>

	<h3>Replacing Damaged Boards</h3>
	<ol>
		<li>Remove fasteners from damaged board</li>
		<li>Pull board carefully to avoid damaging neighbors</li>
		<li>Cut replacement to match (same width and thickness)</li>
		<li>Pre-stain replacement if fence is stained</li>
		<li>Install with corrosion-resistant fasteners</li>
	</ol>

	<h3>Fixing Leaning Posts</h3>
	<p><strong>For minor lean:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Dig around base of post</li>
		<li>Straighten post using level</li>
		<li>Brace in position</li>
		<li>Pack soil tightly or add concrete</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>For severe lean or rot:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>May require post replacement</li>
		<li>Consider professional repair for structural integrity</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Gate Adjustments</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Sagging gate:</strong> Install anti-sag kit or adjust hinges</li>
		<li><strong>Sticking gate:</strong> Check for swelling, adjust strike plate</li>
		<li><strong>Loose hinges:</strong> Replace with longer screws or relocate</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Vegetation Management</h2>

	<h3>Clear Around Fence</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Trim plants 6-12 inches from fence</li>
		<li>Remove vines that trap moisture</li>
		<li>Clear debris from fence base</li>
		<li>Ensure sprinklers don't hit fence continuously</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Prevent Future Growth</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Apply landscape fabric along fence line</li>
		<li>Use gravel border to inhibit growth</li>
		<li>Regular trimming prevents overgrowth</li>
	</ul>

